{{Infobox religious biography | honorific-prefix = Muni Shri | honorific-suffix = Ji Maharaj | religion = [[Jainism]] | sect = [[Digambara]] | birth_date = {{Birth date|1957|9|20|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Sagar, Madhya Pradesh]] | birth_name = Virendra Kumar Singhai | death_date = {{Death date and age|2015|3|13|1957|9|20|df=y}} | father = Jeevan Kumar Singhai | mother = Asha Devi | initiator = ''[[Acharya (Jainism)|Acharya]]'' [[Vidyasagar (Jain monk)|Vidyasagar]] | initiation_date = {{start date|1982|8|20|df=y}} |image=File:Kshamasagarnainagiri.jpg |caption = Portrait at [[Nainagiri]] memorial}} {{Jainism}} Muni '''Kshamasagar''' was a ''[[Digambara monk]]'' initiated by ''[[Acharya (Jainism)|Acharya]]'' [[Vidyasagar (Jain monk)|Vidyasagar]].<ref>[http://www.pradeshtoday.com/newsdetails.php?news=Kshmasagr-chef-Smadimrn&nid=110792 क्षमासागर महाराज का समाधिमरण, Pradesh Today, 13 March, 2015]</ref> He was one of the most followed Jain monks. He is also known for his poetry and writings which are widely quoted.
==Life== Kshamasagar was born in the city of [[Sagar, Madhya Pradesh]] on 20 September 1957.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jnanpith.net/author/muni-kshamasagar|title=Bharatiya Jnanpith|website=jnanpith.net|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref> His father Virendra Singhai was a nephew of famous Sagar philanthropist Singhai Kundanlal, who was a longtime supporter of [[Ganesh Varni]].<ref>Ganesh Prasad Varni, Meri Jivan Gatha, Part 2, 1977, p.355-356</ref> He was initiated as a ''[[Digambara monk]]'' on 20 August 1982 by ''[[Acharya (Jainism)|Acharya]]'' [[Vidyasagar (Jain monk)|Vidyasagar]]. He did his M. Tech from [[Sagar University]] and renounced the worldly life soon afterwards.<ref name=patrika>{{citation |url=http://www.patrika.com/news/sagar/samadhi-jain-muni-kshamasagar-1008987 |title=मुनिश्री क्षमासागर ने ली समाधि, 50 हजार श्रद्धालु हुए शामिल, 50 |work=[[Rajasthan Patrika|Patrika]] |date=13 March 2015 }}</ref>
He died on 13 March 2015 at 6.00 AM in Moraji Jain temple during his ''[[Chaturmas]]'' period. More than 50,000 people attended his funeral proceedings.<ref name=patrika/><ref>{{citation |url=http://loktej.com/?p=4691 |title=क्षमा सागर महाराज जी का समाधी मरण |work=[[Loktej]] |date= }}</ref>
==Works== Kshamasagar wrote "In Quest of the Self: The Life Story of Acharya Shri Vidyasagar", a biography of his teacher ''Āchārya'' Vidyadagar.<ref>Kshamasagar (2007), In Quest of Self : The life story of Acharya Shri Vidyasagar, Delhi: Bhartiya Jnanpith, {{ISBN|81-263-1166-5}}</ref>
His poems have been collected and published in Hindi and English.His poetry works include the following published books. # "Pagdandi Suraj Tak" (1992) # "Muni Kshamasagar ki Kavitayen" (1996).<ref>[http://www.patrika.com/news/sagar/jain-saint-death-in-sagar-1009187/ वर्णीभवन मोराजी में मुनिश्री क्षमासागर महाराज का समाधिमरण, Patrika, 2015-03-13]</ref> # Mukti (2000) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.remadhav.com/products/Mukti.html|title=Mukti - Remadhav Publications (P) Ltd|website=www.remadhav.com|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref> # "Apna Ghar" (2005)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jnanpith.net/book/apna-ghar|title=Bharatiya Jnanpith|website=jnanpith.net|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref> # "Aur Aur Apna" (2016) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jnanpith.net/book/aur-aur-apna|title=Bharatiya Jnanpith|website=jnanpith.net|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref> # "Karam Kaise Karein" is a collection of his discourses.<ref>[http://files.jain.us.com/shrish/4.books/Karam_Kaise_Karein.pdf Karam Kaise Karein, Muni Kshamsagar, Pub. Maitree Samooh, 2009]</ref> # He also wrote "Jain Darshan Paribhashika Kosh".<ref>[http://files.jain.us.com/shrish/4.books/Jain_Darshan_Muni%20Kshamsagar%20ji.pdf Jain Darshan Paribhashika Kosh, Muni Kshamsagar, Gyanodaya Vidyapitha,]</ref>
